  "text": "We next turn our attention to global broadcast. We consider a straightforward global broadcast algorithm that uses our local broadcast strategy as a subroutine. We prove that this algorithm solves global broadcast with probability at least 1 − , in O(D + log(n/ )) · ∆ 1/ττ 2 / log ∆) rounds, where D is the diameter of G, andτ = min{τ, log ∆}. Notice, for τ ≥ log ∆ this bound reduces to O(D log ∆ + log ∆ log (1/ )), matching the near optimal result from the standard radio network model. As with local broadcast, we also prove the degradation of this performance as τ shrinks to be near optimal. (See Table 1 for a summary of these results and pointers to where they are proved [CITATION_1] The broadcast algorithm from [CITATION_2] requires O(D log n + log 2 n) rounds, whereas the corresponding lower bound is Ω(D log (n/D) + log 2 n). This gap was subsequently closed by a tighter analysis of a natural variation of the simple Decay strategy used in [CITATION_3] 2 To make it match exactly, set ∆ = n and = 1/n, as is often assumed in this prior work.",
